## Vector DB Use Case

A traditional keyword-based database search would not be sufficient for searching large legal contracts using natural language questions. Keyword search only matches exact words or phrases in the document. However, legal documents often contain complex language and synonyms, meaning that the exact keywords used in a question may not appear in the text.

For example, a lawyer might ask "What are the termination clauses?" but the contract may use phrases like "agreement cancellation conditions" or "conditions under which the contract may end." A keyword-based search might fail to return relevant results because the wording is different.

Vector databases solve this problem by using embeddings that capture the semantic meaning of text rather than just the exact words. Each sentence or paragraph in the contract can be converted into a vector representation using an embedding model. When a lawyer asks a question in plain English, the question is also converted into a vector.

The vector database then performs similarity search to find the contract sections that are semantically closest to the query. This allows the system to retrieve relevant legal clauses even when the wording is different.

In this system, the vector database would store embeddings of contract sections and enable fast similarity search across hundreds of pages of legal text. This approach makes natural language querying possible and greatly improves the efficiency of legal research.
